We recommended that Management:
Instruct the City Engineer, with the assistance of the OIC-City Planning and Development Officer (CPDO), to:
Provide status report on the implementation of aforementioned development projects, including the reasons for non-implementation;
Develop a clear implementation plan with a defined timeframe and regularly prepare monitoring reports to track progress; and
Supervise the implementation of development projects and conduct regular inspections to ensure timely completion;
Direct the OIC-CPDO to conduct a re-evaluation of the development projects under Continuing Appropriations to determine whether they remain necessary or have become no longer relevant, in order to facilitate the possible re-alignment of funds to more appropriate development project/s;
Require the CPDO, with the assistance of the BAC, to prioritize procurement of the unimplemented projects under the 20 percent DF;
Instruct the CPDO to meticulously plan and evaluate the feasibility of each development project funded out of the 20 percent DF to ensure that these are procurement-and-implementation ready for efficient execution; and
Direct the City Budget Officer and the City Accountant to revert the remaining unexpended balances of appropriations of completed projects from Continuing Appropriations to the unappropriated surplus of the General Fund.

We recommended that Management:
Instruct the City Accountant, in coordination with the City Treasurer, to collect the LD totaling ₱486,545.08 from the concerned suppliers by deducting the same from any money due or which may become due to them;
Require the BAC, in coordination with the GSO, to closely monitor the delivery of goods to prevent incurrence of delay;
Direct the City Accountant to ensure that LD are strictly imposed on suppliers in case of incurrence of delay in the delivery of goods; and
Instruct the BAC to rescind the contract and impose appropriate sanctions over and above the LD to be paid by the suppliers whenever the computed LD reaches 10 percent of the contract price for incurrence of delay in the delivery of goods without valid cause.

Direct the BAC to facilitate and prioritize the procurement of PPAs under the 20% DF; 

Direct the OIC-CPDO to re-evaluate the developmental PPAs under Continuing Appropriations, whether these PPAs are still needed or no longer necessary so that the same may be re-aligned to more appropriate PPAs; and

Direct the City Budget Officer and City Accountant to revert the remaining unexpended balances of appropriations of completed projects from Continuing Appropriations to the unappropriated surplus of the General Fund and re-program these for other development projects.

Instruct the BAC to strictly adhere to the requirements and procurement procedures set forth in the 2016 Revised IRR of RA No. 9184 in order to attain the government policy of competition, transparency, economy and efficiency in the procurement process;

Direct the TWG and BAC to include in their post qualification a comparative evaluation showing the key personnel listed and assigned by the same bidder and list of equipment for different projects with simultaneous date of implementation; and

Instruct the BAC to set limits for the number of contracts to be handled by key personnel to ensure reasonableness of performance without sacrificing quality and timeliness of the projects.

We recommended that:

The City Government ascertain that transfer of funds/financial assistance must be released only to NGOs/POs which meet the requisites for entitlement to government funds pursuant to 4.4 of COA Circular No. 2007-001 dated October 25, 2007;

The City official, responsible for the review of the project proposal or application for funding by the NGO/PO, must ensure that the latter has the capacity to undertake the project, has previously implemented similar project and the purpose of the establishment of NGO corresponds to the objective of the financial assistance.

We recommended that Management:
Require the City Assessor to facilitate the preparation of the updated Report on Real Property Assessment and furnish a copy thereof to the City Treasurer for updating the RPTAR;
Instruct the City Treasurer to provide the City Accountant a copy of the RPTAR which will serve as the basis for setting-up RPT/SET Receivables to reflect the actual collectibles from real property tax in the City’s financial statements;
Require the City Accountant to take up in the books the delinquent accounts amounting to ₱5,359,255.89; and
Direct the City Treasurer to update the Certified List of Tax Delinquencies as of December 31, 2023, by reporting all tax delinquencies, not only for the last five years and furnish a copy to the City Accountant and the Audit Team.

We recommended that Management:
Instruct the OIC-CPDO, in coordination with the OIC-City Engineer, to integrate all sectoral plans, especially in relation to infrastructure projects to ensure timely implementation and procurement;
Direct the OIC-CPDO and the OIC-City Engineer to monitor periodically project sites with indefinite suspension and recommend to the City Mayor the lifting of such suspensions; and
Instruct the OIC-CPDO, in coordination with the City Assessor’s Office, to verify the title of lot intended for the project, ensuring that ownership is transferred to the City Government and checking for any issues or concerns related to the title;

