We recommended that
Management:
a. Direct the Supervising Administrative Officer (SAO) under the SP Office to refrain from procuring goods through reimbursements and adopt alternative methods of procurement pursuant to Section 48 of the 2016 Revised IRR of RA No. 9184 in order to promote economy and efficiency and ensure that the most advantageous price for the government is obtained;
b. Instruct the City Accountant to ensure that payments are made by check directly payable to the creditor in order that applicable withholding taxes can be deducted and remitted to the national government;
c. Instruct the SAO to limit expenses for meals and snacks during committee hearings and are based on the actual participants only in order to avoid unnecessary expenditures and if the meals are necessary for the regular sessions, it shall be charged against the Representation Allowances of the City Officials concerned; and
d. Instruct the City Accountant, in coordination with SAO under the SP Office, to submit the lacking documents to establish the validity of the claims.

We reiterated the previous year’s audit recommendation that Management: 
Require the Inventory Committee to conduct physical count of all road networks in the LGU’s jurisdiction and instruct them to prepare and submit complete Report on Physical Count of Local Road Network (RPCLRN);
Direct the City Engineer to provide the City Accountant and the General Services Officer with the complete description and cost segregation of road components for all existing road projects to facilitate recording in the books and the preparation of subsidiary ledgers for road and its components;
Require the City Accountant and the General Services Officer to maintain complete and updated Local Road Network Ledger Cards and Property Cards, respectively, for each road component of every road network;
Instruct the City Accountant to provide depreciation cost for the road networks account and to check and verify the recorded road networks previously carried in the Registry of Public Infrastructures if these were included in the inventory and still existing, and make the necessary adjustment in the books to reflect the correct balance of the account; and
Ensure the implementation of the accounting and reporting guidelines of COA Circular No. 2015-008 dated November 5, 2015.

We recommended that the Local Chief Executive:

Require the City Accountant to continue to issue demand letters to city officials and national employees concerned to remind them of their responsibility to settle their unliquidated cash advances, and employees who were already resigned or transferred to other office, to cause the liquidation or settlement of their unliquidated balances;

Instruct the City Accountant to ensure completeness of the required supporting documents in the processing of claims in the granting of cash advances;

Direct the City Accountant to stop the practice of granting additional cash advance to official and employee unless the previous cash advance granted have been liquidated;

Require the City Accountant to strictly monitor the submission of liquidation reports to ensure timely accounting thereof to avoid undue accumulation of outstanding cash advances; and

Require the City Treasurer to withhold the salaries of the city officials and employees concerned with unliquidated cash advances pursuant to Section 9.0 of COA Circular No. 2012-004 considering that they have been notified and given more adequate time to liquidate their cash advances.

In view of the foregoing, we recommended that the Local Chief Executive:

Instruct the BAC Secretariat and the City Accountant to submit the lacking documents including the above-mentioned documents submitted with deficiencies to the Audit Team to support the payment made to the contractor and for technical evaluation and inspection, and to ensure that all disbursement vouchers are properly and duly supported with complete documentation;

