The accuracy and completeness of hospital services including professional fees and cost of drugs, medicines, medical supplies billed to patients of San Carlos City Hospital could not be readily established;

The existing organizational structure and job description of several personnel hinder the immediate determination of persons accountable for the accuracy and completeness of reported revenue collections, inventory and receivable balance;
violates Sections 2, 123 and 124 of PD 1445, and Section 170 of RA 7160.

Require the Information Technology and Computer Services Office to study, design and develop a customized Hospital Information System Application Software for San Carlos City Hospital to ensure that the necessary internal control features, listed below, are integrated into the system to:

ensure correct billing and collection of hospital services rendered to patients;

ensure correct billing and collection of cost of drugs, medicines, and medical supplies served to patients;
readily establish the correct balance of drugs, medicines, and medical supplies inventory at the Hospital Pharmacy;

readily establish the correct balance of medical supplies at the Central Supply Section of the city hospital; ensure the immediate printing of correct Abstract of Collections and Daily Report of Collection and Deposit; and ensure the immediate printing of accurate and real time financial and operational reports.

The design of the Hospital Information System should integrate operation and accounting information, on top of the regular reports required by the Department of Health, to ensure proper management and control of city hospital operation.

Security features such as the electronic review and approval of encoded transaction shall likewise be imbedded into the system to protect and ensure information integrity.

Moreover, require the Management Audit Analyst IV to prepare an Operations Manual of San Carlos City Hospital to ensure uniform implementation of approved systems and procedures. The manual should include proper segregation of responsibilities and non-assignment of incompatible functions to only one person.

Further, require the Human Resource Management Officer to review and update organizational set-up of San Carlos City Hospital. Personnel handling cashiering function must be reporting directly to the Office of the City Treasurer but detailed only in San Carlos City Hospital. Personnel designated to conduct internal auditing work must not be allowed to authorize transactions and supervise administrative office operation. 

In addition, the city government shall:

officially designate three (3) cashiers for the three (3) work shifts in the city hospital to readily establish accountability for daily cash collections; officially designate the three (3) Dispensers for the three work shifts to readily establish accountability for the accuracy of balances of drugs, medicines, and medical supplies in the pharmacy; if warranted, hire additional Pharmacist to complete the three (3) work shifts requirement for hospital pharmacy operation.     

